ğŸ“Š Key sorting algorithm comparison table

Algorithm Name Mean Time Complexity Space Complexity Stability Key Features
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Bubble Sort                O(nÂ²)    O(1)         âœ…   Alignment by repeated comparison of adjacent elements. Simple but inefficient.
Selection Sort             O(nÂ²)    O(1)         âŒ   Choose the smallest value and place it in front. The number of comparisons is constant.
Insertion Sort             O(nÂ²)    O(1)         âœ…   Insert a new value into the part that is already aligned; advantageous for nearly aligned data.
Merge Sort                 O(n)     O(n)         âœ…   Divided Conquest Base. Always constant performance, using recursive structures.
Quick Sort       Average O(nlog),   O(log n)     âŒ   Divided conquering around pivot. Very good average performance.
                   Worst O(nÂ²)
Heap Sort                 O(n-log)  O(1)         âŒ   Using the Heap Data Structure. The sorted order can be configured immediately.
Counting Sort             O(n + k)  O(n + k)     âœ…   integer based alignment. Very fast when the value is small in range and integer.
Radix Sort                O(nk)     O(n + k)     âœ…   Sort by digit. Useful for sorting numbers, strings.
Bucket Sort               O(n + k)  O(n + k)     âœ…/âŒ data distributed across buckets and then aligned. Effective for even distribution data.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Please refer to:
- âœ… Stable sort: Relative order of elements of the same value is maintained
- Space complexity means additional memory usage
- k is a range of values (e.g. k = maximum - minimum in coefficient alignment)

